.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBcodata\fP(3) is a Fortran library providing the fundamental physical
constants published by the CODATA.
.TP
.B
Fortran API
exposes the constants as derived type codata_constant_type
which carries:
.RS
.IP \(bu 3
name
.IP \(bu 3
value
.IP \(bu 3
uncertainty
.IP \(bu 3
unit
.RE
.TP
.B
C API
exposes a structure codata_constant_type that defines
the same members as in Fortran:
.RS
.IP \(bu 3
name
.IP \(bu 3
value
.IP \(bu 3
uncertainty
.IP \(bu 3
unit
.RE
.TP
.B
Python
exposes a dictionary with the keys being:
.RS
.IP \(bu 3
the name
.IP \(bu 3
the value
.IP \(bu 3
the uncertainty
.IP \(bu 3
the unit
.SH NOTES
The latest values (2022) do not have the year as a suffix in their name
whereas older values (2010, 2014, 2018) feature the year as a suffix.
All constants are declared with the same variable name in Fortran, C,
and Python.
.SH EXAMPLE

Example in Fortran
.PP
.nf
.fam C
    program example_in_f
    use codata
    implicit none
    print '(A)', '########## EXAMPLE IN FORTRAN ##########'
    print '(A)', '# VERSION'
    print *, "version = ", version()
    print '(A)', '# CONSTANTS'
    print *, "c = ",  SPEED_OF_LIGHT_IN_VACUUM%value
    print '(A)', '# UNCERTAINTY'
    print *, "u(c) = ", SPEED_OF_LIGHT_IN_VACUUM%uncertainty
    print '(A)', '# OLDER VALUES'
    print '(A, F23.16)', "Mu_2022(latest) = ", MOLAR_MASS_CONSTANT%value
    print '(A, F23.16)', "Mu_2018 = ", MOLAR_MASS_CONSTANT_2018%value
    print '(A, F23.16)', "Mu_2014 = ",  MOLAR_MASS_CONSTANT_2014%value
    print '(A, F23.16)', "Mu_2010 = ",  MOLAR_MASS_CONSTANT_2010%value
    end program

